  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Four people, Eli, Joy, Paul, and Sam, want to form a company with 16 shares. Each person must get a positive integer number of shares, and all 16 shares must be given out. No one person can have more shares than the other three people combined. Assuming that shares are indistinguishable, but people are distinguishable, in how many ways can the shares be given out?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "To solve this problem, we need to find the number of ways to distribute 16 shares among 4 people, with the given constraints. Since each person must get a positive integer number of shares, we can represent the number of shares each person gets as a non-negative integer combination of 16. We also know that no one person can have more shares than the other three people combined, so the maximum number of shares any one person can have is 16 - 3 = 13. The problem is now equivalent to finding the number of non-negative integer solutions to the equation x1 + x2 + x3 + x4 = 16, where xi ≤ 13. This is a classic problem of distributing indistinguishable objects (shares) into distinguishable boxes (people), which can be solved using the stars and bars method. The number of ways to distribute the shares is given by the formula (n + k - 1) choose (k - 1), where n is the number of shares (16) and k is the number of people (4). Plugging in the values, we get (16 + 4 - 1) choose (4 - 1) = 19 choose 3 = 969. However, this counts all possible distributions, including those where one person has more than 13 shares. We need to subtract the number of distributions where one person has more than 13 shares. We can calculate this by considering the number of ways to distribute the shares among the remaining 3 people, which is (16 - 13) choose 3 = 3 choose 3 = 1. Since there are 4 people, we need to subtract this number 4 times, so the total number of valid distributions is 969 - 4 = 965.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>965</answer>"
}

