  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Consider a $2 \times n$ grid of points and a path consisting of $2n-1$ straight line segments connecting all these $2n$ points, starting from the bottom left corner and ending at the upper right corner. A path is called efficient if each point is only passed through once and no two line segments intersect. How many efficient paths are there when $n=2016$?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "To solve this problem, we can use combinatorics and the concept of lattice paths. We can think of the path as a sequence of $2n-1$ steps to the right and $n-1$ steps upwards, where each step to the right or upwards represents a line segment. The total number of efficient paths is then the number of ways to choose $n-1$ steps out of $3n-2$ total steps to be upwards (the remaining steps will be to the right). This is a binomial coefficient, given by $\binom{3n-2}{n-1}$. When $n=2016$, this gives $\binom{6030}{2015}$. Using the formula for binomial coefficients, we get $\frac{(6030)!}{2015!(6030-2015)!} = \frac{(6030)!}{2015!2015!}$. Calculating this, we get a very large number.",
  "final_answer": "<answer></answer>"
